04150nam a22006255i 9780292798595DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212003txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927985957 a10.7560/7124612doi  a(DE-B1597)587060  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF395.M5 ǂb C37 2003eb 7aSOC0310002bisacsh04a305.8687207644090451 aCarroll, Patrick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFelix Longoria's Wake :bBereavement, Racism, and the Rise of Mexican American Activism /cPatrick Carroll. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2003  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tFOREWORD -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER ONE. Only in South Texas: Working and Educational Conditions in the Nueces Strip -- tCHAPTER TWO. The Incident -- tCHAPTER THREE. The Principal Actors in the Drama -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Mobilization of Nueces Basin Mexican and Anglo Towns -- tCHAPTER FIVE. State, National, and International Politics -- tCHAPTER SIX. The Burial -- tCONCLUSION -- tNOTES -- tWORKS CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPrivate First Class Felix Longoria earned a Bronze Service Star, a Purple Heart, a Good Conduct Medal, and a Combat Infantryman's badge for service in the Philippines during World War II. Yet the only funeral parlor in his hometown of Three Rivers, Texas, refused to hold a wake for the slain soldier because "the whites would not like it." Almost overnight, this act of discrimination became a defining moment in the rise of Mexican American activism. It launched Dr. Héctor P. García and his newly formed American G.I. Forum into the vanguard of the Mexican civil rights movement, while simultaneously endangering and advancing the career of Senator Lyndon B. Johnson, who arranged for Longoria's burial with full military honors in Arlington National Cemetery. In this book, Patrick Carroll provides the first fully researched account of the Longoria controversy and its far-reaching consequences. Drawing on extensive documentary evidence and interviews with many key figures, including Dr. García and Mrs. Longoria, Carroll convincingly explains why the Longoria incident, though less severe than other acts of discrimination against Mexican Americans, ignited the activism of a whole range of interest groups from Argentina to Minneapolis. By putting Longoria's wake in a national and international context, he also clarifies why it became such a flash point for conflicting understandings of bereavement, nationalism, reason, and emotion between two powerful cultures—Mexicanidad and Americanism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMexican AmericanszTexasxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh1 aLimón, José E.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71246140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292798595423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292798595/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK